{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17493350","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17493350"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T07:07:06+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T07:07:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1296"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1296","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1296"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.15,0.15,0.1,0.52]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1296"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58482"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1296","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1296"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1296"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43898"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"1"},{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"106"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"1674"},{"type":"tags","id":"2602"},{"type":"tags","id":"2706"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11627"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1179"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1188"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14780"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17710"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42277"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44630"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44697"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58482","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/58482"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 60-year-old man is evaluated on day one post open nephrectomy for a renal mass. The procedure was uncomplicated and he is currently on an epidural infusion of fentanyl and bupivacaine for analgesia. He has no other relevant background history. He had a pre-operative echocardiogram which was unremarkable. On examination, his pulse rate is 150/min, blood pressure 80/50mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, and temperature 35.9\u00b0C. His oxygen saturation is 100% oxygen on 4L. His peripheries are cool. The rest of the examination is unremarkable. Two 14G cannulas are inserted and 1L of isotonic saline rapidly infused. Despite this, the blood pressure remains low at 87/50mmHg. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn ECG is performed (Image). Blood is collected for urgent analysis. The complete blood examination and arterial blood gas are normal. The biochemistry and troponin level are pending.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate definitive treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Pacemaker","Locate and control the source of bleeding","Cease epidural infusion","Adenosine","Electrical cardioversion"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has acute postoperative atrial fibrillation. Atrial fibrillation is a type of atrial tachycardia that causes uncoordinated activity in the atria. It usually presents with tachycardia and \u003Cstrong\u003Eirregularly irregular rhythm\u003C/strong\u003E with no discernable P waves on the ECG. The management of atrial fibrillation depends on the haemodynamic status of the patient. Haemodynamically unstable patients should get \u003Cstrong\u003Eemergent electrical cardioversion \u003C/strong\u003E(with sedation and consent) to bring back the heart rhythm to normal. Haemodynamically stable patients are treated with a \u003Cstrong\u003Erate-control\u003C/strong\u003E (or rhythm control) strategy. The drugs of choice for rate-control are beta-blockers (or calcium channel blockers). Since atrial fibrillation is also associated with the thromboembolic phenomenon, anticoagulation is considered for patients depending on their thromboembolism risk and time of onset of atrial fibrillation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA pacemaker is indicated for patients with sinus node dysfunctions (eg, persistent bradycardia) or symptomatic AV blocks.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt is unlikely that the patient has an internal source of bleeding that is causing hypotension. IV fluids would likely have improved the hypotension temporarily if the underlying cause was hypovolaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEpidural infusion with bupivacaine has a risk of causing arrhythmias. However, the most common arrhythmia associated with bupivacaine toxicity is ventricular arrhythmia which presents with heart rate \u0026gt;200/min and indiscernible/widen QRS complex on ECG.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAdenosine is the drug of choice for paroxysmal supraventricular tachycardia (SVT: eg, AV nodal reentrant tachycardia). It produces transient complete AV block to discern the ECG in atrial fibrillation/flutter where tachycardia makes reading the ECG difficult. However, this patient\u0027s ECG is typical of atrial fibrillation. Moreover, several studies have shown that adenosine increases the risk of atrial fibrillation. Hence, it should not be used in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Atrial fibrillation causing haemodynamic instability should be managed with electrical cardioversion"],"references":["Nusair M, Flaker GC, Chockalingam A. Electric cardioversion of atrial fibrillation. Mo Med. 2010 Jan-Feb;107(1):59-64."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43898"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1296"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"15358"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"15358","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/15358"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/95d6507e-b0d8-4a0e-8740-e4a5632a9ec4.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/95d6507e-b0d8-4a0e-8740-e4a5632a9ec4.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":800,"height":411}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43898","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/43898"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-01T09:09:48+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-02T09:16:15+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1296"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58482"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"1","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/1"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude34","name":"Anaesthesia","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"36","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/36"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd43","name":"Urology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description